      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Adelaide ¶ 22nd Jany 1887 ¶ Baron F. Von Mueller K.C.M.G. &amp;c &amp;c. ¶ Melbourne ¶ Dear Sir,...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.01.22</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From David Lindsay</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">ML MSS.200/1, item 1, letter book, p. 430, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Adelaide</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">22nd Jany 1887</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron F. Von Mueller K.C.M.G. &amp;c &amp;c.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As I am preparing a statement of expenses connected with the botanical collection for the S.A. branch of the R.G.S.A. I am desirous of knowing your intentions in regard to the amount promised me by you. Will you very kindly reply at your earliest convenience</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Hoping you are well</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yours very faithfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>David Lindsay</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Surveyor &amp; Explorer<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In "Report of an Exploring Expedition across Australia by David Lindsay" (pp. 165-6) Lindsay wrote: 'From Dalhousie [SA] a collection of plants were sent to the Honorable The Minister For Education to be forwarded to Baron Von Mueller for classification. In this collection as well as in all others subsequently transmitted there were, as far as possible, three specimens of each plant so that one complete set could be kept by the Baron, and one by the Geographical Society leaving another for Lieutenant Dittrich and myself to dispose of as we might consider fit.' [ML MSS.200/1, item 2, (1887-90)].</p>
               </note>
            </p>
         </div>
